Solution: # Spin Angular Momentum of a Proton

The magnitude of spin angular momentum is given by:
$$L_s = \hbar\sqrt{s(s+1)}$$

where:
- $s = 1/2$ for a proton (spin-1/2 particle)
- $\hbar = 1.055 \times 10^{-34}$ J·s

Calculating:
$$L_s = \hbar\sqrt{\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{1}{2}+1\right)} = \hbar\sqrt{\frac{1}{2} \times \frac{3}{2}} = \hbar\sqrt{\frac{3}{4}}$$

$$L_s = 1.055 \times 10^{-34} \times \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} = 1.055 \times 10^{-34} \times 0.866$$

$$L_s = 9.14 \times 10^{-35} \text{ J·s}$$

Converting to units of $10^{-35}$ J·s:
$$L_s = 9.14 \times 10^{-35} \text{ J·s} = 9.14 \text{ (in units of } 10^{-35} \text{ J·s)}$$

